 {smodule}{python-kwargs}  

 {nparagraph}  
The first \sn{subroutine?argument} passing feature we want to discuss is the  
use of \sns{keyword argument}, which gets around the problem of having to remember  
the position of an argument of a multi-parameter \sn{subroutine?function}.  
    {nparagraph}  

 {frame}[label=slide.kwargs,fragile]  
   {Argument Passing in \python: Keyword Arguments}  
 {itemize}  

 {sdefinition}[id=def.default-argument]

\varseq{pseq}{1,\ellipses,n}{\comp{p}_{#1}}  
\varseq{aseq}{1,\ellipses,n}{\comp{a}_{#1}}  
\varseq{vseq}{1,\ellipses,n}{\comp\pmetal{val}\comp\pmetar_{#1}}  
The last $\natlethan{k}n$ of $n$ parameters of a \sn{subroutine?function} can  
be \definame[post=s]{keyword argument} of the form  
\lstinline[mathescape]|$\pseq{i}$=$\vseq{i}$|: If no argument $\aseq{i}$ is given in  
the function call, the \definame{default value} $\vseq{i}$ is taken.  
    {sdefinition}  

 {sexample}[id=default-argument.ex,for=default value]  
The head of the \lstinline|open| \sn{subroutine?function} is  
\lstinputmhlisting[linerange=1-2]{python/code/open.py}  
Even if we only call it with \lstinline|open("foo")|, we can use  
\sns{subroutine?parameter} like \lstinline|mode| or \lstinline|opener| in  
the \sn{subroutine?body}; they have the corresponding  
\sn{default value}.  

We can also give more arguments via keywords, even out of order  
\lstinputmhlisting[linerange=3-3]{python/code/open.py}  
    {sexample}  
    {itemize}  
    {frame}  

 {nparagraph}[title=BTW]  
\usemodule{python/slides/lambda?python-lambda} The \lstinline|opener| argument of  
\lstinline|open| is a \sn{subroutine?function}, and often an  
\sn{python-lambda?anonymous function} is used if it is specified.  
    {nparagraph}  
    {smodule}  
    {document}  


